    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The idea of \"terminal neuroplasticity failure\" is a common misconception; while chronic stress can downregulate receptors, the brain's inherent resilience usually allows for re-sensitization given enough time and the right interventions. Research shows that even in cases of severe depletion, the biological machinery does not permanently \"die,\" but rather requires a specific, often non-obvious, combination of treatments to reset the system. Your experience of feeling empty is a powerful signal that your current approach isn't working, but it is not proof that a biological wall exists; it simply means the path forward hasn't been found yet.",
